  "prompt": "How do you know when you are going into the friendzone?",
  "response": "Recognizing the signs that you might be entering the \"friendzone\" can be subjective, but there are common indicators that people often notice. Here are some signs to watch for:\n\n1. **Lack of Romantic Interest**: If the person you like frequently talks about other romantic interests or shows a lack of interest in pursuing something deeper with you, this could be a sign.\n\n2. **Limited Physical Affection**: If your interactions lack physical touch or affection that typically accompanies romantic relationships (like hugging, holding hands, etc.), it may indicate that they see you as just a friend.\n\n3. **Group Settings**: If they prefer to hang out in groups rather than one-on-one, this may suggest they're not inclined to explore a romantic connection.\n\n4. **Friendship Language**: When the person uses pet names, jokes about being friends, or frequently expresses how much they value your friendship, it could signal that they see you strictly as a friend.\n\n5. **Noticing Boundaries**: If they set clear boundaries regarding intimacy or personal space, it may indicate they are not interested in more than friendship.\n\n6. **Slow to Respond**: If they are unresponsive or take a long time to reply to messages, especially when compared to how they interact with others, this might suggest a lack of romantic interest.\n\n7. **Direct Conversations**: Sometimes, the clearest sign is when they explicitly say they see you as a friend or talk about relationships in a way that excludes you as a romantic partner.\n\n8. **Emotional Support Role**: If you find yourself in the position of being their emotional support or therapist, it might indicate that they view you as a friend rather than a potential partner.\n\nWhile these signs can indicate a friendzone scenario, communication is key. If you're unsure about your relationship status, it may be worthwhile to have an open and honest conversation with the person about your feelings.",
